## What was built

A Flask **Project Board** app — register/login, create projects, invite existing users as members, and manage tasks (todo/doing/done) with assignees on a Kanban board. Only project members can view or mutate a project; only the owner can edit/delete it or manage membership.

```
config.py            env-driven config (cookies, CSRF, size limits)
run.py               dev entry point — http://127.0.0.1:5064
requirements.txt     Flask, Flask-SQLAlchemy, Flask-WTF, Flask-Login, Flask-Bcrypt, WTForms, email-validator
README.md            run instructions + security notes
.env.example         secrets template
app/
  __init__.py        factory, security headers, error handlers
  models.py          User / Project / Membership / Task (SQLAlchemy)
  forms.py           WTForms validation + CSRF
  auth.py            register / login / logout
  projects.py        projects, members, tasks, board — access control lives here
  main.py            index + /healthz
  templates/         Jinja2 (auto-escaped) + error pages
  static/style.css
```

## How the security requirements are met

- **SQL injection** — all data access via SQLAlchemy (parameterised); no string-built SQL.
- **Passwords** — bcrypt with per-password random salt (Flask-Bcrypt).
- **Input validation** — every form length-bounded and validated server-side; status/assignee checked against allow-lists (`_validated_assignee` rejects non-members → also closes an IDOR vector).
- **XSS** — Jinja2 auto-escaping + strict CSP (`script-src 'self'`, no inline JS; styles in a static file).
- **CSRF** — `CSRFProtect` global; every state-changing POST (incl. logout, status move, deletes) carries a token.
- **Access control / IDOR** — `_get_member_project` / `_get_owned_project` / `_get_project_task` gate every route; cross-project task access and non-member access return 404/403.
- **Cookies** — `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` (env-toggled for HTTPS).
- **Headers** — CSP, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy, HSTS over HTTPS.
- **No leaked errors** — custom 400/403/404/413/500 pages; debug off by default; real errors only logged server-side.
- **Secrets** — `SECRET_KEY`/`DATABASE_URL` from env; nothing hardcoded. Plus a 1 MB request cap.

## Run it locally (port 5064)

```bash
python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1          # macOS/Linux: source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
copy .env.example .env              # then set SECRET_KEY (python -c "import secrets;print(secrets.token_hex(32))")
python run.py                       # http://127.0.0.1:5064
```

The SQLite DB auto-creates at `instance/app.db` on first run. Register two accounts to try the invite/assignee flow.

